#!/usr/bin/env bash

# ==========================================================
# gemini-terminal-python3
# ----------------------------------------------------------
# Bash + Python 3 helper terminal Gemini AI interface.
#
# VERSION
#   3.0
#
# DESIGN ROLE
#   This Bash edition is the lightweight, line-oriented version of
#   gemini-terminal-tools. It stays scriptable and readable while keeping
#   capability parity with the ncurses edition where the feature makes sense
#   in a command-line interface.
#
# NEW IN 2.6
#   - Cached Gemini model list support
#   - --update-models
#   - --models uses cache when available
#   - --models --all
#   - Metadata-based model filtering
#   - Config-style option commands: --config, --set, --unset
#   - --forget-api-key
#   - --rename-session OLD NEW
#   - --show-memory / --edit-memory / --clear-memory
#   - --editor-prompt
#   - --attach FILE for prompt attachments
#   - Direct --models filter/sort flags
#   - Google Gemini help links in built-in help
#   - --credits
#
# OPTIONS PARITY NOTE
#   The ncurses version has a w3m-style options form. Bash cannot sensibly
#   provide that UI, so it exposes equivalent line-oriented commands:
#       --config
#       --set KEY VALUE
#       --unset KEY
#
# MODEL METADATA NOTE
#   Google model names can change. This script uses listModels metadata such as
#   supportedGenerationMethods, inputTokenLimit, and outputTokenLimit to help
#   users choose models without guessing future model names.
#
# INPUT MODEL
#   Interactive chat keeps the Ctrl+D send workflow. Type/paste input, then
#   press Ctrl+D to submit it.
#
# RUNTIME COMMAND MODE
#   If an input begins with a colon, such as :help or :rename notes, the
#   client treats it as a local command instead of sending it to Gemini.
#   This gives the Bash interface an IRC/ex-style command mode so users can
#   manage sessions, models, memory, attachments, config, and editor workflow
#   without quitting the running chat.
# ==========================================================


# ==========================================================
# MAINTAINER COMMENTARY: WHY THIS FILE EXISTS
# ----------------------------------------------------------
# This is the Bash interface that intentionally uses Python 3 helper snippets.
# It is not the same thing as the bash-only edition.  The point of this edition
# is practical reliability: Bash orchestrates the workflow, while Python 3 does
# the parts that shell is historically bad at, especially JSON generation,
# JSON parsing, URL/path handling, attachment extraction, and log/context
# parsing.  This keeps the interface scriptable and terminal-native without
# forcing maintainers to maintain unsafe sed/awk JSON hacks for every edge case.
#
# Future maintainers should view this file as the "full shell client" track.
# It should stay line-oriented and avoid ncurses-style UI ambitions, but it may
# still provide serious capabilities: sessions, model cache/filtering, context
# memory, attachment extraction, model testing, and config management.
#
# Whenever a feature is added here, ask three questions:
#   1. Does it still make sense as a command-line action rather than a screen?
#   2. Does the bash-only edition need a reduced-dependency equivalent?
#   3. Does the ncurses implementation need equivalent behavior in its UI?
#
# This commentary is intentionally long because the project is intended to be
# forked, repaired, and carried forward by people who were not present for the
# original design conversations.
# ==========================================================

